==English==
===Etymology===
From Middle English ''plage'' <Latin ''plāga'' (blow, wound). Cognate with Dutch ''plaag'', German ''Plage'', Swedish ''plåga'', French ''plaie'', Polish ''plaga''.

===Pronunciation=== 
*plāg, /pleɪɡ/, /<tt>pleIg</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-eɪɡ|Rhymes: -eɪɡ]]
*{{audio|en-us-plague.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
'''plague''' ([[plagues]])

#A [[widespread]] [[affliction]], [[calamity]], or [[destructive]] [[influx]] especially when seen as [[divine]] [[retribution]]
#* A '''plague''' of locusts
#The [[disease]] "plague", caused by the [[bacterium]] ''Yersinia pestis'' and mostly known by its variant form ''bubonic plague''
#An [[epidemic]] or [[pandemic]] caused by any [[pestilence]], but specifically by the disease "plague"

